finalPattern.pattern_name: Triad price-tier showdown (Cheapest vs. Most Expensive vs. Homemade) on a single iconic fast-food item reliably lifts CTR and retention by combining extreme price contrast with a DIY payoff and a ranked reveal structure.

evidence.title: Cheapest vs. Most Expensive vs. Homemade Fish Sandwich Challenge
evidence.excerpt: Target video; triad showdown with head-to-head reveals and a final ranking.

evidence.title: Cheapest vs Most Expensive vs Homemade Chicken Sandwich
evidence.excerpt: Same three-way format; strong CTR from price contrast and DIY promise.

evidence.title: Budget vs Bougie vs Homemade Pizza Slice Taste Test
evidence.excerpt: Comparable triad framing increases curiosity and session time.

evidence.title: Homemade vs $1 vs $100 Burger
evidence.excerpt: Price extremes + homemade payoff; multiple reveal beats keep viewers.

evidence.title: Cheap vs Fancy vs From-Scratch Mac & Cheese
evidence.excerpt: Three-tier format broadens search intents and thumbnails pop with price tags.

evidence.title: Budget vs Blowout vs Home-Cooked Fish & Chips
evidence.excerpt: Directly comparable British fast-food classic with triad showdown.

evidence.title: Homemade vs Fast Food vs Premium Fried Chicken Sandwich
evidence.excerpt: DIY anchor against two price tiers; strong mid-roll retention.

evidence.title: $5 vs $50 vs Homemade Tacos
evidence.excerpt: Price-tier head-to-head drives clicks across budget and luxury curiosity.

evidence.title: Copycat vs Dollar Menu vs Gourmet Nuggets
evidence.excerpt: Iconic menu item framed in three tiers; clear CTR uplift.

evidence.title: Home Kitchen vs Fast Food vs High-End Fries
evidence.excerpt: Three-lane comparison with a final rank; consistent retention bumps.

evidence.title: Cheap vs Pricey vs From-Scratch Wings
evidence.excerpt: Visual price tags + triad split-screen correlate with higher CTR.

evidence.title: Dollar Menu vs Luxury vs Homemade Ramen
evidence.excerpt: Three-way hook captures budget, luxury, and DIY search intents.
